{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568311"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19745"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.09,0.03,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90356"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74615"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4247"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34939"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90356"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. During the skin examination, the doctor notices a 5 mm blue-grey papule on her upper back. She reports that the lesion has been present for several years without any change in size, shape, or colour with pressure or over time. She has multiple naevus but this is different from the other naevus on her back.  She admits to sunbathing often as a teenager and would get burnt at times. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works as a public relations officer, spends her weekends bushwalking, and has no relevant family history of skin cancer. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She as fitzpatrick skin type 3. The lesion is shown in the photograph (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blue naevus","Nodular melanoma","Dermatofibroma","Pigmented basal cell carcinoma","Venous lake"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of a stable, well-circumscribed, blue-grey papule that has remained unchanged for several years is highly characteristic of a blue naevus. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlue naevi\u003C/strong\u003E are benign melanocytic lesions that typically appear as solitary, blue to blue-black papules measuring 2-10 mm in diameter. They most commonly occur on the dorsal aspects of the hands and feet, scalp, face, and buttocks, but can appear anywhere on the body. The blue colour results from the Tyndall effect, where melanin pigment is located deep in the dermis, causing shorter wavelengths of light to be scattered more than longer wavelengths. Though they look different from other naevus, the history and confluent blue pigmentation makes other diagnosis less likely.  Lastly, whilst she has a history of sunbathing and burning in the crucial time period for skin health, it is very common occurrence unfortunately in Australia and does not necessarily indicate skin malignancies. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENodular melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely in this case as it typically presents as a rapidly growing, often ulcerated lesion with irregular borders and variable pigmentation. Nodular melanomas tend to grow vertically rather than horizontally and often demonstrate the ABCDE features (Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Colour variation, Diameter \u0026gt;6 mm, and Evolution or change). Whilst the \u0027ugly duckling sign\u0027 of an abnormal naevus is important for being suspicious for melanoma, not all different naevi are malignant. The long-standing stability of this lesion argues strongly against melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a common benign fibrous nodule that typically presents as a firm, pink to brown papule or nodule. It often demonstrates the \u0027dimple sign\u0027 when pinched (central depression). While dermatofibromas can less commonly be pigmented, they rarely have the uniform blue-grey colour characteristic of blue naevi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPigmented basal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a pearly papule with telangiectasia and often has a rolled border. While it can appear pigmented, it usually shows areas of ulceration or crusting over time and tends to grow slowly but progressively, unlike the stable nature of the lesion described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous lake\u003C/strong\u003E is a vascular lesion that appears as a dark blue to purple, soft, compressible papule. They are most commonly found on sun-exposed areas, particularly the lips, ears, and face of elderly individuals. While they can appear blue, they are typically compressible and may blanch with pressure, features not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlue naevi are generally benign and do not require treatment unless there are cosmetic concerns or diagnostic uncertainty. If there is any doubt about the diagnosis, or if the lesion shows any changes in appearance, excisional biopsy should be considered for histopathological confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blue naevi are benign melanocytic lesions characterized by a blue-grey to blue-black appearance due to the Tyndall effect.","Blue naevi are typically stable in size and appearance over time, distinguishing them from melanoma.","Dermatoscopic features of blue naevi include homogeneous blue pigmentation without melanoma-specific structures."],"references":["Borgenvik TL, Karlsvik TM, Ray S, let al.  Blue nevus-like and blue nevus-associated melanoma: a comprehensive review of the literature. ANZ J Surg. 2017; 87:345-49."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74615"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19745"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21697"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21697"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3jT4qPwKNuTzQU7eGSK10uSOvgQYlW.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3jT4qPwKNuTzQU7eGSK10uSOvgQYlW.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":429}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74615"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T18:59:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T08:36:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90356"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","lin